To Cook Barela,<br><br>
Honorable men can never be made dishonorable by the actions of others. Men disgrace themselves. The Marine Corps can't ever be dishonored or disgraced.<br><br>
To Joe Deleva,<br><br>
A couple of messages ago, in reference to the Winter Soldiers, you stated how &quot;hearsay doesn't count&quot;. Earlier in the message you stated how incidents that were described by the Winter Soldiers weren't commonplace. &quot;This is far from true&quot; were your words. What do you base this on? Were you there? Or are you listening to &quot;hearsay&quot;?<br><br>
I don't need to listen to Winter Soldier testimony to form an opinion. I was there. You suggested a consensus to find out if injustices were widespread. What is your definition of widespread? You would be hard pressed to find individuals who had NOT seen incidents of abuse. How many are going to come forward and say they saw these things, when their words are viewed as attacks on fellow soldiers - or are simply dismissed as &quot;hearsay&quot; by wannabes?<br><br>
What is the point in having dialogue in good faith if only testimony which tickles our ears is listened to?<br><br>
I'm still waiting for your email address, Joe.<br><br>
To Joe A,<br><br>
Assuming you are a vet who disobeyed a direct order, you belonged on the garbage truck. If you think that your post somehow adds good sense to this discussion or credence to Vietnam Veterans, you are woefully mistaken.<br><br>

